The patient’s history of recent cardiac catheterization with stent placement increases the risk of cholesterol emboli, especially given the finding of intravascular spindle-shaped vacuoles on renal biopsy — a hallmark of cholesterol embolization syndrome. The presence of eosinophilia (11%) and systemic inflammatory markers like elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate further support a post-embolic process. Other options lack supporting evidence: renal papillary necrosis typically involves focal lesions without characteristic vacuolation; eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and polyarteritis nodosa would usually present with more widespread vasculitic changes and no mention of lipid-related triggers.

